She took me waaaayyyy longer than I anticipated. I feel like I get to finicky with details. I’m trying to learn how to let things just be and embrace those small fuck ups and not over complicate things. But it’s bloody hard when I’m so in my head about everything 🫣 also I love how she turns from happy to sad in the jump of a clip - classic Jacqueline work right there - always gotta be melancholy don’t they 🙄 I added doves and Lillie’s to the piece because I was listening to a podcast ( @artholespodcast ) speak about the church in one of the the Toulouse-Lautrec episodes and it made me feel some type of way. So ofcourse gotta include some catholic symbolism in there as a way to cope with the traumas of growing up catholic 💁🏻‍♀️ let me know if you feel some type of way about this piece. Always interested in hearing opinions of my work and if it resonates with you 😘

Part TWO of my thrift flipping series!! 🎨
When I’m looking for a canvas to thrift flip, I love the ones where the person had a vision, but then kind of gave up after getting started. You know, the ones where they spent a lot at the art shop and not on art shop brand canvases, but on GOOODD canvases. Also, I’m no stranger to throwing away art projects and spending a small fortune on a project I hated and gave to an op shop so I feel your pain. 

Here’s to everyone who’s given up on art projects - you’re the real ones.👌👌

The last few weeks have been filled with some sweet moments spent painting. It seems that the looseness of my paintings has really come into its own - I’m really adapting the post impressionist painterly way of creating these new pieces. 

Oftentimes when I am tattooing I also find that I am drawing on the same techniques as those that I use when I am painting using high contrast and key focal points in pieces to create more depth for a better tattoo. I absolutely love how both forms of being are interwoven in my work.

Thrift flip part 3! The reason why I’m obsessed with crawling panthers is because the original illustration that inspired this traditional tattoo was created by Author Marie Schubert who wrote and illustrated the book Minute Myths and Legends in 1934. It was then picked up by pioneers of tattooing such as Don Ed Hardy, Amund Dietzel and Professor Grimshaw and made its way onto various tattoo flash sheets world wide in the 50s and 60s. Absolutely LOVE tattooing a classic and putting even more feminine energy into it so now you know why it’s super special to me!

Just put the finishing touches on this lovely lil Pierrot clown oil painting and I’m kind of over the moon about how it turned out. Ofcourse I painted over a piece I wasn’t so thrilled about…
The colors really represent that melancholic vibe I always strive for in my work which just speaks to my soul, ya know?

I poured my heart into this piece, capturing the essence of Pierrot’s quiet charm. There’s something so enchanting about the way he wears his emotions on his ruffled collar.  It’s the delicate balance between laughter and sorrow, the art of finding beauty in vulnerability. Pierrots reflect the complexity of human emotions, reminding us to embrace our fragility and celebrate our uniqueness.

Let me know if you would like prints of this piece in the comments! ❤️✨

This was a thrifted wood panel I turned into a lovely portrait painting to enhance the framing. The original painting on it was scratched and unloved. I gave the wood panel some love and oil-painted this delicate beauty on it.
One of my favorite steps in this process is the application of a gloss coat. This final touch not only enhances the overall aesthetics of the painting but also brings out the vibrant colors in a way that truly makes the artwork come alive. The glossy finish not only adds a layer of protection but also serves as a visual amplifier, making the hues pop with intensity and providing a captivating sheen that further elevates the appeal of the painting. 

This will be available for purchase at @hogtownflea this weekend! ✨❤️

I thrift flipped a charming yet neglected vintage wood panel. My initial steps involved meticulously stripping away layers of paint and refining the surface with a thorough sanding, resulting in a pristine canvas. 
I wanted the “frame” to be a nice glossy dark chocolate colour to go with Ophelias side profile.
The subsequent stages involved the meticulous application of gesso and then finally starting the oil painting. I’ve found I love oil painting on wood panel - you have to really work in lots of super light layers to achieve soft blends with colours. The enchanting ethereal quality of Ophelia has become a personal favorite of mine.🩶
